collections.name: The Cone-Man Collection
collections.description:
Meet the Cone Man the smooth, expressive soul of the smoke culture. Each NFT in this collection captures a distinct vibe, mood, or moment from Cone Man’s world. From chill to hype, mellow to lit Cone Man is a reflection of all of us who keep it real, stay fresh, and roll with purpose.

This collection isn’t just about art. It’s about building.

Proceeds from Cone Man NFT sales go directly into growing My Empties™, our premium rolling paper and cone company. We are on a mission to level up the smoke game. We're raising funds to expand our product line, reach more smokers, and bring the always fresh lifestyle to life.

We’re inviting our community—fans, customers, collectors, and culture lovers—to build with us from the ground up. Own a Cone Man, own a piece of the journey.

collections.name: A Cry for Jewish Memory
collections.description:
✡️ "Listen to the Ashes" – A Cry for Jewish Memory
They never asked for war.
They never wanted fire, nor chains, nor walls.
They simply wanted to pray, to pass down, to love, to exist.

And yet...

They were driven from their lands, thrown out of their homes, branded like animals, betrayed by their neighbors.
They endured centuries of humiliation, exile, pogroms, caricatures, and absurd accusations.
They were called thieves, parasites, god-killers.
They were treated as foreigners even where their ancestors had been buried for a thousand years.

Then came the machine.
Cold.
Industrial.
Inhuman.

Children cried silently in trains with no windows.
Mothers held their sons' hands one last time in lines that led nowhere.
Entire families were swallowed by camps where even the sky stood silent.
And in the smoke of the crematoria, there were names, voices, dreams—no one hears anymore.

But it’s not over.

Even today, the insults return.
The stares grow hard again.

collections.name: The Lion Man and the Pirate
LiLiROZE
collections.description:
Liliroze was born in Geneva. Her passion for photography is initiated in her early years due to the discovery of her father’s pictures, but it’s only later, after a master in econometrics, that she decides to devote all her time and energy to the art of photography. She settles in Paris, obtains her diploma at Louis Lumière School in 1997 and starts being of photographer. Winner of the first prize of the Pictures of the year 2009 and 2024, (portrait and still life).Her work has been exhibited in France, Switzerland, Brasil, China and Morroco.

A first monography has been edited in 2012, Confidences, (HC Editions) and a second one in 2024, Ici et Ailleurs (Hemeria Editions).

“I don’t photograph what I see, but what I feel. I like slowness and long exposure, which allow breathing and heart beats. I photograph almost without light. What comes out of the shadow is poetry, that tastes like a dream and looks like a secret.”

collections.name: Bonac Sleeper B-COA
collections.description:
In the storied landscape of East Hampton, New York, where the traditions of the Bonac baymen are as enduring as the sea, there lived a man known as Mr. Leland. Unlike most, Mr. Leland was not only versed in the ways of the sea but also in the art of resurrection—of machines.

One sultry summer day, Mr. Leland stumbled upon a barn-find that would set the stage for an unforgettable project—a neglected 1989 Mustang LX notchback, hidden beneath layers of dust and time. His heart beat faster as he envisioned what could be: a classic American muscle car reborn through sheer grit and innovation.

The locals knew Mr. Leland as a man who thrived on proving the impossible possible. When a few doubters at the East Hampton dock wagered that he couldn’t meld the raw power of yesteryear with today’s technology, Mr. Leland only smiled, his plan already forming.
